// Regression: auto-guard `return;` UB in promoted `int main()`.
//
// User writes `void main()`. The compiler auto-promotes to `int main(void)`
// (BUG-603). If a runtime safety check (auto-guard for unproven array index,
// MMIO bounds, or @cstr overflow) fires, it must emit `return 0;` — bare
// `return;` in `int main(void)` is undefined behavior under C99/C11:
//
//   - gcc -O0: exit code 0 (eax happens to be zeroed)
//   - gcc -O2: exit code 208 (eax holds whatever)
//   - gcc warns "return with no value, in function returning non-void"
//
// Fix is in emit_safety_early_return (emitter.c): checks
// current_main_promoted and emits `return 0;` for void main, `return;`
// for true void functions. Test trips the path by defeating VRP with a
// loop-mediated assignment and then accessing the unprovably-bounded array.
u32[4] arr;
void main() {
    u32 i = 0;
    for (u32 k = 0; k < 1; k += 1) { i = 99; }
    // VRP cannot prove i < 4 here — auto-guard inserts:
    //   if ((size_t)i >= 4u) { return 0; }  ← was `return;` (UB)
    u32 v = arr[i];
    arr[0] = v;
}
